<main class="col">
  <h2>What that axis is</h2>
  <p>Dimension 1 of this embedding is not a vibe. It correlates with eigenvector centrality at r&nbsp;=&nbsp;0.99996 &mdash; your position is literally the sum of your neighbors&rsquo; positions. It measures one thing: how many companies you touch, weighted by how connected those companies are. And on that axis the two labs are in a different league from everyone else, with Anthropic clearly out front:</p>
  <div class="statrow">
    <div class="stat a"><div class="v">45</div><div class="k">distinct partners for Anthropic &mdash; the most connected node in the agentic economy</div></div>
    <div class="stat o"><div class="v">30</div><div class="k">for OpenAI, second place</div></div>
    <div class="stat"><div class="v">18</div><div class="k">for third-place Microsoft &mdash; nobody else is close</div></div>
  </div>

  <h2>Where the lead comes from</h2>
  <p>Break Anthropic&rsquo;s edges down by category and the story writes itself: the coding-agent lane goes 11&ndash;0. Cursor, Windsurf, Cognition, Replit, Bolt, Lovable, Sourcegraph, Augment, Tabnine, Zencoder, Factory &mdash; the tools that write the world&rsquo;s code run on Claude. Everything else is close: fintech and banks 10&ndash;8, other agent startups 7&ndash;6, and the two labs share the same safety-eval bench almost exactly (Apollo, METR, Gray Swan, Haize, Irregular work with both).</p>
  <p>We stress-tested the lead by re-running the embedding on counterfactual graphs. It survives every slice: keep only independently verified edges, drop shared-investor ties, drop rivalry edges (that one <em>widens</em> it). The only thing that kills it is deleting Anthropic&rsquo;s edges until both labs have the same partner count &mdash; at which point it becomes a coin flip, with OpenAI&rsquo;s average partner slightly better connected. The lead is pure breadth: Anthropic simply shows up in 50% more of the agentic economy&rsquo;s wiring.</p>
</main>

