  <p style="margin-top:1rem">Read the columns together and the pattern is clean. Anthropic leads everywhere businesses spend money on models. OpenAI leads everywhere scale is measured in people, gigawatts, or security clearances. These are not two companies at different points in the same race; they are two different theories of where the value in AI accrues, both currently working.</p>

  <h2>Three more things the graph knows</h2>
  <p><strong>The labs are wired like agent companies, not like labs.</strong> A stochastic block model over the graph, told to find its own communities, refuses to put Anthropic and OpenAI in a &ldquo;frontier lab&rdquo; bloc &mdash; both get sorted with the agent startups, because commercially that is how they behave. The research-lab category is a label; the wiring says product company.</p>
  <p><strong>The government lane flipped in one day.</strong> In February 2026 Anthropic refused Pentagon terms covering mass surveillance and autonomous-weapons use. Federal agencies were directed to drop Claude the same week, and OpenAI announced a Department of War deal within hours of the news. A court paused the ban in March and the fight is ongoing &mdash; but structurally, one lab now runs on classified networks and the other litigates. Refusing a customer on principle is the single most expensive product decision visible anywhere in our data.</p>
  <p><strong>The labs have started buying the agent-security layer.</strong> The most decision-relevant lab fact in our dataset isn&rsquo;t a coordinate: OpenAI acquired Promptfoo, one of the companies on our own rivals list, in 2025. When frontier labs start doing M&amp;A in the layer that red-teams and secures agents, that layer stops being a niche &mdash; which is, of course, why we work in it.</p>

  <h2>The bottom line</h2>
  <p>Is Anthropic pulling ahead of OpenAI? In the agentic economy &mdash; the network of companies building on, deploying, and securing AI agents &mdash; yes, measurably, and the lead is structural: it shows up in the wiring itself, survives every robustness check we could throw at it, and matches the enterprise spending data. In the consumer, compute, and government arenas OpenAI remains the larger fact of the world. The interesting part is that both leads are getting bigger at once. The race stopped being one race sometime in 2025, and the map is where you can see it.</p>
</main>

